 106:     RDRAND(seed=None, *, retries=10)
 107: 
 108:     Container for the hardware RDRAND random number generator.
 109: 
 110:     Parameters
 111:     ----------
 112:     seed : None
 113:         Must be None. Raises if any other value is passed.
 114:     retries : int
 115:         The number of times to retry. On CPUs with many cores it is possible
 116:         for RDRAND to fail if heavily utilized. retries sets the number of
 117:         retries before a RuntimeError is raised. Each retry issues a pause
 118:         instruction which waits a CPU-specific number of cycles (140 on
 119:         Skylake [1]_). The default value of 10 is recommended by Intel ([2]_).
 120:         You can set any value up-to the maximum integer size on your platform
 121:         if you have issues with errors, although the practical maximum is less
 122:         than 100. See Notes for more on the error state.
 123: 
 124:     Attributes
 125:     ----------
 126:     lock : threading.Lock
 127:         Lock instance that is shared so that the same bit git generator can
 128:         be used in multiple Generators without corrupting the state. Code that
 129:         generates values from a bit generator should hold the bit generator's
 130:         lock.
 131:     seed_seq : None
 132:         Always None since RDRAND cannot be seeded.
 133: 
 134:     Notes
 135:     -----
 136:     RDRAND is a hardware random number generator that is available on Intel
 137:     processors from the Ivy Bridge line (2012) or later, and AMD processors
 138:     starting in 2015.
 139: 
 140:     RDRAND has been audited and is reported to be a secure generator. It is
 141:     **much slower** than software BitGenerators and so is only useful in
 142:     applications where security is more important than performance.
 143: 
 144:     **State and Seeding**
 145: 
 146:     Results from ``RDRAND`` are **NOT** reproducible.
 147: 
 148:     ``RDRAND`` uses a hardware generated seed and so cannot be seeded. The
 149:     state contains a single integer value ``status`` that takes the value 1
 150:     if all calls have succeeded and 0 if any fail. A failure of a call to
 151:     RDRAND does not propagate, and so users much check this value to determine
 152:     if results are random.
 153: 
 154:     **Parallel Features**
 155: 
 156:     ``RDRAND`` is stateless and so multiple instances can be used in parallel.
 157: 
 158:     >>> from randomgen import Generator, RDRAND
 159:     >>> rg = [Generator(RDRAND()) for _ in range(10)]
 160: 
 161:     **Exceptions**
 162: 
 163:     Bit generators are designed to run as quickly as possible to produce
 164:     deterministic but chaotic sequences. With the exception of RDRAND, all
 165:     other bit generators cannot fail (short of a massive CPU issue). RDRAND
 166:     can fail to produce a random value if many threads are all utilizing the
 167:     same random generator, and so it is necessary to check a flag to ensure
 168:     that the instruction has succeeded. When it does not exceed, an exception
 169:     should be raised. However, bit generators operate *without* the Python GIL
 170:     which means that they cannot directly raise.  Instead, if an error is
 171:     detected when producing random values using RDRAND, the Python error flag
 172:     is set with a RuntimError.  This error must then be checked for. In most
 173:     applications this happens automatically since the Lock attached to this
 174:     instance will check the error state when exiting and raise RuntimError.
 175: 
 176:     If you write custom code that uses lower-level function, e.g., the
 177:     PyCapsule, you will either need to check the status flag in the
 178:     state structure, or use PyErr_Occurred to see if an error occurred
 179:     during generation.
 180: 
 181:     To see the exception you will generatr, you can run this invalid code
 182: 
 183:     >>> from numpy.random import Generator
 184:     >>> from randomgen import RDRAND
 185:     >>> bitgen = RDRAND()
 186:     >>> state = bitgen.state
 187:     >>> state["retries"] = -1  # Ensure always fails
 188:     >>> bitgen.state = state
 189:     >>> gen = Generator(bitgen)
 190: 
 191:     The next command will always raise RuntimeError.
 192: 
 193:     >>> gen.standard_normal(size=10)
 194: 
 195:     The RDRAND-provided function ``random_raw`` also checks for success
 196:     and will raise if not able to use RDRAND
 197: 
 198:     >>> bitgen.random_raw()
 199: 
 200:     Note that ``random_raw`` has been customized for the needs to RDRAND
 201:     and does not rely on the Lock to raise.  Instead it checks the status
 202:     directly and raises if the status is invalid.
 203: 
 204:     Finally, you can directly check if there have been any errors by
 205:     inspecting the ``success`` property
 206: 
 207:     >>> bitgen = RDRAND()
 208:     >>> assert bitgen.success  # True
 209:     >>> bitgen.random_raw(10)
 210:     >>> assert bitgen.success  # Still true
 211: 
 212:     You will only ever see an AssertionError if the RDRAND has failed.
 213:     Since you will first see a RuntimeError, the second assert will not
 214:     execute without some manual intervention.
 215: 
 216:     **No Compatibility Guarantee**
 217: 
 218:     ``RDRAND`` is hardware dependent and not reproducible, and so there is no
 219:     stream guarantee.
 220: 
 221:     Raises
 222:     ------
 223:     RuntimeError
 224:         If RDRAND is not available on the platform.
 225: 
 226:     Examples
 227:     --------
 228:     >>> from randomgen import Generator, RDRAND
 229:     >>> rg = Generator(RDRAND())
 230:     >>> rg.standard_normal()
